    <!-- Page header -->
    <header class="pub-header">
      <h1>Hospital Hero — Inclusive, Haptic-supported Journey</h1>
      <a class="btn secondary" href="/assets/projects/hospital-hero/report.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View Full Report (PDF)</a>
    </header>
    <hr class="rule">

    <!-- Intro / Overview -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="lead">
        We enhanced the <em>Hospital Hero</em> app so children with visual or auditory impairments can prepare for hospital visits with confidence—by layering <strong>tactile interaction</strong> and an <strong>inclusive UI</strong> across the whole journey. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}
      </p>

      <div class="keywords" style="margin-top:14px">
        <span class="tag">Pediatric eHealth</span>
        <span class="tag">Inclusive design</span>
        <span class="tag">Haptics</span>
        <span class="tag">System & journey thinking</span>
      </div>

      <ul style="margin-top:14px; color:var(--sub)">
        <li><strong>My role:</strong> Research & concept lead (strategy, mapping, concept system, writing)</li>
        <li><strong>Team:</strong> Heimin Kang, Joost Spaanderman</li>
        <li><strong>Course:</strong> eHealth Design 2025</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Background -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Background</h2>
      <p>
        Hospital Hero helps children and parents reduce anxiety around hospital procedures using preparation, storytelling, and light gamification; it is used in multiple Dutch hospitals. However, the current experience is not sufficiently inclusive for children with sensory impairments. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
      </p>
      <p>
        Literature and prevalence data underline why accessibility matters: children with sensory impairments often experience higher fear and anxiety in clinical contexts, which can negatively affect cooperation and outcomes. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
      </p>

      <h3 class="subhead">Design Goal</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>Make Hospital Hero inclusive and engaging without stigma</strong>—empowering children with a sense of control, reducing uncertainty, and supporting the whole care journey for families and staff. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Process -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Process</h2>

      <h3 class="subhead">System & Stakeholder Understanding</h3>
      <p>
        We mapped stakeholders (children, parents, clinicians, administrators) and positioned Hospital Hero within micro/meso/macro layers to clarify value and integration points. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}
      </p>

      <h3 class="subhead">Research Synthesis → Requirements</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Foster <strong>control</strong> and reduce uncertainty for children. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}</li>
        <li>Deliver <strong>stigma-free accessibility</strong> (beneficial to all, not “special mode”). :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}</li>
        <li>Keep it <strong>engaging</strong> for both impaired and non-impaired children. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}</li>
        <li>Integrate improvements across the <strong>whole journey</strong> (before–during–after). :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="subhead">Ideation & Expert Input</h3>
      <p>
        Using HMW ideation and a 2×2 (Inclusivity × Engagement), we selected a primary concept—<em>Tactile Interaction in the Hospital Journey</em>—with a supporting sub-concept for <em>Inclusive UI</em>. We iterated with experts (e.g., Visio; haptics maker Tellmies) to refine feasibility, content timing, and interaction fidelity. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}
      </p>

      <h3 class="subhead">Inclusive UI Guidelines (Highlights)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>High contrast visuals, bolder outlines; enlarge tap targets and icons.</li>
        <li>Consistent voice-over / read-aloud; optional text zoom; tablet-friendly layout.</li>
        <li>QR codes with contrast borders; reduce background distraction on focus. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Outcome -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Outcome</h2>
      <p>
        We deliver a cohesive concept that embeds tactile interaction and inclusive UI across three phases:
      </p>

      <h3 class="subhead">Before the visit</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Haptic storytelling</strong>: vibrations match narrative events (e.g., heartbeat pulse), easing unfamiliarity while learning. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="subhead">During the visit</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Haptic animal search</strong>: BLE/NFC floor stickers guide children like a “warmer/colder” game (stronger pulses nearer the target). :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}</li>
        <li><strong>Calm with animal</strong>: brief breathing + vibration routine to regulate anxiety between steps. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-sensory exploration</strong>: tactile patches linked to app content (materials, device sounds). :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="subhead">After the visit</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Haptic reward</strong>: a celebratory vibration pattern reinforces accomplishment and confidence. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}</li>
        <li><strong>Haptic notification</strong>: gentle cues help children move to the next step with a sense of control. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="subhead">Impact</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Micro</strong>: more accessible, engaging preparation; better emotional comfort for children and families. :contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}</li>
        <li><strong>Meso</strong>: smoother procedures and reduced burden for staff. :contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}</li>
        <li><strong>Macro</strong>: healthier perceptions of hospitals; improved health motivation & literacy. :contentReference[oaicite:19]{index=19}</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="subhead">Next</h3>
      <p>
        Prototype & validation with children (with/without impairments), co-design with haptics experts and pediatric psychologists, then phased rollout starting from inclusive UI baseline. :contentReference[oaicite:20]{index=20}
      </p>
    </section>

